Scientists have found an animal that can live 500 years
An international group of biologists has concluded that the longest-lived vertebrate animal is the Greenland shark, which can live for about 500 years.
Scientists conducted a radiocarbon analysis of the lens of the eye of 28 Greenland sharks.
The largest shark, which is over five meters long, can be between 272 and 512 years old.
Biologists believe that a low metabolism, which leads to slow development, plays an important role in the shark&#39;s longevity.
Female Greenland sharks reach sexual maturity only by the age of 150.
It was previously believed that the &quot;neighbor&quot; of the shark, the bowhead whale, lives the longest of all vertebrates.
The oldest individual known to scientists was just over 210 years old.
