Pokémon Go, decent hunting for health and happiness
It&#39;s exciting to watch the world change.
That teenagers and children no longer go out to play, preferring to spend their free time looking at screens, has been a complaint by many over the past decade.
Pokemon Go gets people off the couch and into some physical activity.
Screen time was originally limited to television, then video games, and more recently smartphones.
It&#39;s so great to see that technology and outdoor activity are not mutually exclusive.
I&#39;m referring, of course, to the craze that is Pokémon Go, a character-based app originally created for video games in the 1990s (which has since spawned a series of cartoons, playing cards, and other offshoots).
