The largest M&amp;A deal has started on the pension market - KIT Finance Pension Administrator launched the process of merging four controlled NPFs.
As a result, on the basis of the Gazfond Pension Savings, an NPF will be created with a savings volume of about 373 billion rubles.
The launch of the procedure for merging four pension funds - KIT Finance, Promagrofond, Naslediye and Gazfond Pension Savings - was announced yesterday by the owner of 100% of the funds, LLC KIT Finance Pension Administrator.
&quot;The reorganization is carried out in agreement with the Central Bank, subject to the requirement of non-deterioration of the terms of existing contracts,&quot; the company said in a statement.
The merger is being carried out on the basis of the Gazfond Pension Savings.
According to Oleg Byaloshitsky, General Director of this NPF, the merger of funds allows us to solve several problems: expanding the geography of presence, concentrating resources for development, reducing costs, replicating the best practices of each of the funds and optimizing corporate governance.
According to him, the estimated completion date for the consolidation is the second quarter of 2017.
As a result of the merger of NPF &quot;Gazfond Pension Savings&quot; will become the largest player in the OPS market.
As of March 31, the volume of pension savings of the merging funds exceeded 373 billion rubles.
As follows from the reports on the website of the funds, the beneficiaries of their owner, KIT Finance Pension Administrator, are currently Anatoly Gavrilenko (owns 65% through controlled LLCs) and NPF Gazfond (35%).
However, the group itself launched the association much later than its competitors.
Thus, the NPF &quot;Future&quot; controlled by the O1 group absorbed &quot;Stalfond&quot; at the beginning of this year.
At present, this united NPF is merging the Uralsib and Russian Standard funds.
&quot;Unification into a single structure, in addition to reducing costs, is necessary to solve structural problems,&quot; notes Nikolay Sidorov, general director of the NPF &quot;Future&quot;.
Active work on the consolidation of funds since April has been going on in the pension group &quot;Safmar&quot; - NPF &quot;European&quot;, &quot;Education and Science&quot; and &quot;Regionfond&quot; should join the NPF &quot;Safmar&quot; before the end of this year.
In 2017, NPF &quot;Doverie&quot; will join them.
&quot;The merging of funds will give the effect of strengthening control over risks, operational processes and costs,&quot; the Safmar pension group noted.
The pause in the merging of funds, which KIT Finance Pension Administrator has withstood, can be caused by several reasons, experts point out.
Until recently, NPFs could not redeem more than 40% of the issue of infrastructure bonds in which the group was actively placed.
After amendments to the Central Bank&#39;s resolution in March of this year for a number of issuers that meet the requirements of the regulator, such restrictions no longer exist.
If necessary, the entire issue can be bought out by one major player,&quot; says Yury Nogin, director of the ACRA Financial Institutions Ratings Group.
Several heads of NPFs from the top 15 in terms of assets cite the separation of spheres of influence and, as a result, personnel appointments in a single fund, which the owners of the group had to agree on, is another possible reason for the pause.
Yesterday Anatoly Gavrilenko was not available for comment.
The NPF Gazfond also did not respond to Kommersant&#39;s request.
Although the consolidation of funds is a laborious and expensive undertaking, in the long run this decision will be justified.
According to Sergey Okolesnov, general director of the Pension Partner consulting company, Gazfond Pension Savings has fewer outflows, and the merger will help stabilize the base of the group&#39;s other funds.
At the same time, the more successful experience of NPF &quot;KIT Finance&quot; and &quot;Promagrofond&quot; in building retail sales of OPS, as well as using more modern software, will be in demand.
The requirements of the Central Bank to the processes and personnel of NPFs are constantly growing, therefore it is not advisable to duplicate the infrastructure at four funds with a single investment policy, says Pavel Mitrofanov, managing director for corporate ratings at Expert RA.
&quot;The effect of the reduction of duplicating functions will unequivocally block the possible costs of merging,&quot; Mr. Mitrofanov notes.
Sergei Okolesnov estimates the cost of merging the four funds at 30-50 million rubles.
&quot;The cost of maintaining four funds of this size is about 400 million rubles a year, with consolidation in the medium term, the budget can really be halved,&quot; Mr. Okolesnov is sure.
The kindest Disney movie &quot;Pete and his dragon&quot; was released in Russian rental.
Beautiful views of New Zealand, a touching dragon, a heartbreaking story and songs in country style are enough to believe in old-fashioned magic again, says ELENA KRAVTSUN.
The frightened baby was picked up by a dragon, who became a human cub and a gentle nanny, and a devoted friend.
Pete names his friend Elliot, after a puppy from a book of fairy tales, plays catch-up with him and falls asleep in an embrace.
Six years later, overgrown and in a loincloth, he can no longer be distinguished from another intelligent forest tomboy - Mowgli.
In this form, Pete is discovered by the red-haired female gamekeeper Grace (Bryce Dallas Howard), while the brigade of Gavin (Karl Urban), her husband&#39;s brother, aggressively cuts down the forest.
Now she will not only have to believe in the existence of the dragon, but also help save him.
Pete takes a crash course in &quot;being human&quot; surrounded by idyllic Americans who wear cowboy shirts, have a moral code in their hearts, and smile brighter than any advertisement.
No character looks or acts too terrible for the viewer to truly hate or fear.
Even Gavin, who opened the hunt for an atypical inhabitant of the forests subject to him, is far from an incorrigible villain.
The huge fluffy dragon also turned out not to be scary at all, with a kind bulldog muzzle, an airliner&#39;s wingspan and the ability to become invisible.
The dragon hums funny, purrs, even grunts and, fortunately, does not speak, but you always want to stroke him, this compares favorably with all known cinematic dragons.
Elliot&#39;s visual image and demeanor provide such a high degree of emotional involvement that in the most tense moments, not only small spectators, but also adults begin to sob desperately into three streams.
Surprisingly good is the underage Oakes Feegley as Pete, torn between a possible family and a true friend.
And Robert Redford masterfully gives out the canonical grandfather, which literally every child would be glad to have.
How did director David Lowry manage to pull off a fantastically cute remake of the forgotten 1977 Disney film Pete&#39;s Dragon, mediocre from nose to tail and remembered only for its mix of animation and live-action cinema, and make it the most heartfelt movie of the summer?
Nothing but a miracle helped.
In his painting, Lowry from the original, in fact, took only two things: the orphan Pete and the dragon.
Musical numbers and most of the strange jokes were left behind.
In this kind fairy tale, features borrowed from &quot;Bambi&quot;, &quot;Alien&quot; and many other children&#39;s pictures dear to the heart are read.
Disney Studios continues to successfully expand the gallery of high-quality remakes of the XXI century.
Of course, &quot;Pete and the Dragon&quot; is not as stunningly beautiful as the same &quot;The Jungle Book&quot;, and it does not have the masterful villain that Cate Blanchett turned out to be as a stepmother in the new &quot;Cinderella&quot;.
But this naive film no less successfully helps to believe in miracles and goodness in the best Disney traditions.
By the way, director Lowry will receive the keys to Disney&#39;s magic castle again - for the artistic film adaptation of the story about &quot;Peter Pan&quot;.
David Lowery and screenwriter Toby Halbrooks worked as a tandem in &quot;Pete and His Dragon&quot; in an ambitious new project about a boy who does not grow up based on the fairy tale of the same name by James Barry.
