The Spiritual Administration of Muslims (DUM) of Tatarstan refuses to use the Russian language in mosques.
Yesterday, the plenum of the DUM obliged its imams to conduct Friday sermons only in Tatar, in order to force young Tatars to &quot;learn their native language.&quot;
The department says it &quot;in no way infringes&quot; the rights of Muslims of other nationalities.
In some mosques in Kazan, they complain that up to 60% of the parishioners do not understand the Tatar language, including foreign students, migrants and the Tatars themselves.
Imams fear that their sermons in Tatar &quot;will not reach the entire audience.&quot;
Yesterday, the plenum of the Muslim Muslim Spiritual Board of Tatarstan unanimously decided to hold Friday sermons in the mosques of the republic only in the Tatar language.
As Mufti of Tatarstan Kamil Samigullin said, this should be an incentive for young Tatars to &quot;learn their native language.&quot;
&quot;For those who say it&#39;s &#39;difficult&#39;, we intend to organize Tatar language lessons absolutely free of charge in every large mosque,&quot; Mr. Samigullin promised.
He added that &quot;the decision has already entered into force&quot; and today in all mosques sermons &quot;should already be in the Tatar language.&quot;
He recalled that the DUM of Tatarstan publishes the magazine &quot;Shura&quot; with typical sermons in the Tatar language.
An imam who does not speak Tatar well enough &quot;can thoroughly prepare for them.&quot;
The DUM of Tatarstan unites more than a thousand parishes in all municipalities of the republic.
According to the mufti, Friday sermons in the districts are conducted exclusively in the Tatar language.
At the same time, a number of mosques in Kazan previously used predominantly Russian.
In particular, as the mufti pointed out, this was practiced in the Burnaevskaya mosque, Zakabannaya and Eniler.
However, Mr. Mukhametshin emphasized, the leadership sets the task that all students should speak both state languages of the republic, regardless of nationality.
&quot;There can be no question of any infringement of non-Tatar Muslims,&quot; Mr. Mukhametshin emphasized, explaining that the sermon itself &quot;is not an obligatory, main part of the prayer.&quot;
At the same time, the prayer itself will continue to be read in Arabic, lectures and lessons in Russian will remain in mosques.
At the same time, Rafik Mukhametshin told Kommersant that there was no serious threat of ousting the Tatar language from mosques.
In addition to Russian and Tatar, other languages, for example, Uzbek or Tajik, according to his information, are not used in sermons in the republic.
The decision of the DUM was actively supported in the executive committee of the World Congress of Tatars (WCT).
The head of the executive committee of the CGT, Rinat Zakirov, told Kommersant: &quot;Mosques are an important part of our national life.&quot;
It would be sad if the Tatar language left this sphere.
He noted that conducting sermons only in the Tatar language is &quot;the desire of the imams themselves&quot;, but the executive committee of the CGT &quot;considers it to be right.&quot;
The imams interviewed by Kommersant, who preached in Russian, are ready to fulfill the decision of the DUM, but they believe that the parishioners will have difficulty understanding the clergy.
Both Tatars and Russians go to the mosque.
Many do not understand the language.
They, of course, will be tight.
&quot;We&#39;ll have to rebuild,&quot; says Farhat Mavletdinov, the imam of the Burnaevskaya mosque.
According to him, sermons in Russian are closer even to many Tatars, since &quot;Russian in schools, kindergartens, on the radio is everywhere from the very beginning.&quot;
However, he believes that the mosque will be able to continue the lessons and lectures in Russian, which are held on other days.
We rely on Allah.
Allah will show a way out of this situation,&quot; he concluded.
But about 60% of us do not know the Tatar language.
These are Uzbeks, and Tajiks, and Azerbaijanis.
Many foreign students visit us: Africans, Arabs.
&quot;That&#39;s why we switched to Russian for four years,&quot; says the imam.
He believes that sermons in the Tatar language will &quot;reach a narrower circle and will not reach the entire audience.&quot;
But we will obey the decision of the plenum.
It&#39;s just that the outcome of the sermons will be different.
But time will tell.
&quot;For example, it will only be easier for me, because the Tatar language is my native language,&quot; Gabdulla Galiullin concluded.
The former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service was put on trial
The Moscow prosecutor&#39;s office approved the indictment in a criminal case investigated by the Main Investigative Committee of the ICR on embezzlement of budget funds allocated for the needs of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
Ex-head of the prison department Alexander Reimer and his deputy, who caused the Federal Penitentiary Service damage in the amount of more than 2.7 billion rubles, will appear before the court.
The Moscow prosecutor&#39;s office sent a criminal case to the Zamoskvoretsky District Court against the former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia Alexander Reimer, his former deputy Nikolai Krivolapov, as well as the director of the Federal State Unitary Enterprise &quot;Center for Information Technology and Communications of the Federal Penitentiary Service&quot; (FSUE TsITOS) Viktor Operedinov.
Depending on the role and degree of participation in the commission of crimes, they are accused by the Main Investigative Committee of the ICR in Moscow under Part 3 of Art. 285 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of official powers that entailed grave consequences), part 4 of Art. 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud committed using one&#39;s official position, as part of an organized group, on an especially large scale).
In addition, Krivolapov is charged under Part 1 of Art. 222 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the TFR, in 2010-2012, these individuals fraudulently stole from the state treasury budget funds allocated by the Federal Penitentiary Service to provide the department with electronic monitoring systems for controlled persons, the so-called electronic bracelets.
To steal budget money, the group members developed a scheme according to which the FSUE TsITOS enterprise under their control, with which relevant state contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision, including &quot;electronic bracelets&quot;, and sold them at prices that were several times inflated.
Despite the fact that FSUE TsITOS did not have production equipment, buildings, facilities for accommodating production facilities that would allow creating a complete cycle for the production of &quot;electronic bracelets&quot;, five government contracts worth more than 3.3 billion rubles were concluded between it and the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
As a result of this scheme, more than 2 billion rubles ended up on the accounts of the Samara branch of the Federal State Unitary Enterprise, of which 1.2 billion rubles. was stolen.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles. Mr. Reimer personally received the cashed funds in his office from one of the accomplices, the criminal case in respect of which was separated into a separate proceeding.
Nikolai Krivolapov, who participated in the fraud, was found to have cartridges for a premium pistol of unknown origin, which allowed him to be charged with additional charges.
In this case, the volume of which amounted to 133 volumes, the Federal Penitentiary Service filed a claim against the accused for compensation for material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion rubles.
