The Blagoveshchensk city court (Amur region) sentenced the former head of the city Alexander Migulya to nine years in a penal colony.
This was reported on Friday, August 12, on the website of the court.
Migulya was found guilty of committing crimes under Articles 286 (“Abuse of authority”), 285.1 (“Misappropriation of budgetary funds”) and 285 (“Abuse of official authority”) of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation.
The investigation found that the official in December 2008 provided his friend with a land plot in the village of Mukhinka in violation of the procedure established by land legislation.
In 2006, he illegally issued a resolution on the acquisition of the city&#39;s ownership of a road bridge across the Chigiri River, at an inflated price without competitive procedures and the conclusion of a municipal contract, Interfax clarifies.
In addition, in the period from 2007 to 2010, Migulya, in the interests of a commercial organization controlled by him, changed the terms of payments under the sale and purchase agreement for the lease of a land plot that was provided for housing construction, and also freed the company from rent.
As a result, the regional budget received less than 5 million rubles, and the city treasury about 21 million rubles.
On August 4, it became known that the former mayor, who is in custody on suspicion of corruption and who was applying for a deputy mandate, did not submit signature lists to the election commission for participation in the elections to the State Duma on time and was removed from the election race.
Migulya was detained in May 2015 in the Lipetsk region and placed in a pre-trial detention center.
Prior to that, he had been on the international wanted list since 2011.
Alexander Migulya served as mayor of Blagoveshchensk from November 2004 to April 2010.
