WSJ: The US is considering imposing sanctions against the Russian Federation due to the hacking of the Democrats&#39; servers.
US officials are considering imposing new sanctions on Russia in response to the hacking of the Democratic Party&#39;s servers, The Wall Street Journal writes, citing sources.
Reportedly, in order to impose sanctions, the administration of US President Barack Obama will have to formally blame Russia or Russian-backed hackers for the attack on the servers.
The FBI and other U.S. intelligence agencies are virtually certain of Russia&#39;s involvement in the cyberattack, the sources said.
The WSJ notes that the US usually prefers not to name those who carry out hacker attacks.
The exception is the 2014 hack of the Sony Entertainment Pictures database, for which the DPRK was officially held responsible.
However, last year Obama issued an executive order making it easier to impose sanctions on those who carry out or facilitate cyberattacks.
It was originally directed against China, but can be used against other countries as well.
The process of deciding on sanctions can be lengthy, the newspaper writes.
Even if officials concluded that the hackers were acting with Russian support, they would have to weigh the possible consequences before making a decision to release information.
They will have to determine whether the incident is serious enough to exacerbate tensions in bilateral relations because of it.
Earlier it was reported that the administration of Barack Obama admits the possibility of sanctions against the state, whose hackers hacked into the servers of the National Committee of the Democratic Party.
WikiLeaks has released the emails of the Democratic National Committee.
The media reported that hackers working with the Russian authorities may be involved in the hack.
The Kremlin called such reports absurd.
FAS fined Google almost half a billion rubles
The reason was the violation of competition in the mobile application market.
The antimonopoly proceedings were initiated at the initiative of Yandex.
The Russian company claimed that Google was giving smartphone makers access to Android components under conditions that prohibited the pre-installation of applications from other developers, in particular from Yandex.
FAS found confirmation of these claims and established that the company abused its dominant position in the market and forced mobile device manufacturers to install other applications along with the Google Play store.
As a result of the audit, the Federal Antimonopoly Service decided to punish Google, said Alexei Dotsenko, deputy head of the FAS.
