In the midst of the rampage of the Olympic Games - the &quot;zen&quot; of trampolining
Wherever you are, no matter how much time it is now, this is the Olympics.
Events in Rio de Janeiro seem fixed and inevitable, a frenzied combination of competition and drive.
As if the Olympic flame itself is that burning torch that is passed from the archer to the swimmer, to the gymnast, to the triathlete.
You can&#39;t turn on the TV, read the newspaper, or eavesdrop on your neighbors in line at the coffee shop and not hear about Simone Biles, Cathy Ledecky, or the Michael Phelps-Chad de Cloes feud.
And then there&#39;s Logan Dooley.
Dooley, a dimpled, handsome newcomer to the Olympics for the first time, could very well be among those prime-time celebrities promoted by sponsors and life-affirming commercials if he were a swimmer, gymnast, or even a fencer.
But Dooley, 28, from Lake Forest, California, is vying for gold in the Olympic trampolining event.
The Olympic flame does not cover all events in the same way.
Further from the center, partly in the shade, are those sports that are not generally recognized: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
Brass will always be with us, long reign to him.
But if I may be allowed to timidly defend my personal predilection, let me draw your attention to the modest charm of trampoline jumping.
Although trampolining has been an Olympic sport since 2000, when it debuted at the Sydney Games, it has received so little recognition in the past 16 years that many of the people I interviewed were not aware that it was an Olympic sport at all.
This may be regional ignorance.
Although the United States sent athletes to compete, it never won a trampoline medal, and its athletes did not reach the finals until 2012.
The Chinese and Russians tend to share the men&#39;s awards, while the Chinese and Canadians share the women&#39;s awards.
Dong Dong of China and Rosie McLennan of Canada will defend their London gold medals this year.
But trampolining has an outsider charm, partly because to the unenlightened ear it is more associated with a college circus than with the Olympics.
Here I must confess that I am not an expert, but only a down-to-earth enthusiast.
They do have comic potential—the caricatured flash of endless jumps—but also the grace of gymnastics and diving, the two sports they basically combine.
The word &quot;trampoline&quot; comes from the Spanish word &quot;el trampolín&quot;, meaning &quot;diving springboard&quot;.
Contenders jump on a giant trampoline, flying nearly 30 feet into the air, and must perform a series of acrobatic stunts (turns, folds and somersaults) before finally landing on their feet.
They are judged on performance, difficulty and &quot;flight time&quot; according to the official program of the Olympic Games.
Thirty-two athletes from 17 countries, 16 men and 16 women, will compete in Rio.
The most common Olympic course is forward.
Medal contenders have to go further, faster, higher and higher in pursuit of gold, sometimes to the finish line, and sometimes back and forth, back and forth across the field.
They aim not only for the finish line or starting wall, but also, in full view of the TV cameras, for another tantalizing milestone: a world or Olympic record.
This stubborn aspiration is noble, admirable, even fanatical - and it is enough to make even the viewer shed a tear.
But it, in my opinion, is somewhat tiring when watching the Games.
From him, jumping on a trampoline gives a respite.
The direction of the trampoline is up.
Moving forward is not the goal.
He or she bounces, seems weightless, like an astronaut, flying up, then down, then effortlessly up again.
And they, of course, are not without competition or difficulties, but during the entire program there is no insane zeal to the finish line, no long jumps, only a marvelous, graceful disappearance of time and gravity.
It is the closest Olympic sport to Zen.
