NBC will broadcast the finale as a daytime program starting at 2:00 pm on both days.
In the midst of the Olympic craziness, a calm, beautiful moment is expected, which can be easily overlooked in the general scuffle.
And if consciousness-raising can only be achieved by subjecting male athletes to coveted stares and objectification—as male gymnasts from the United States have recently suggested, according to the Wall Street Journal—Dooley is just waiting for his new admiring crowd of fans.
&#39;Generation protests&#39; in Ethiopia, longtime US ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia have faced fierce opposition from the government.
Eyewitnesses say dozens of protesters were fatally injured during clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia really on the verge of a split?
Over the past decade, it has been one of Africa&#39;s most stable countries, a solid ally of the West with a booming economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have rocked the country, spreading to more and more of its territories.
In the past week alone, thousands have taken to the streets demanding radical political change.
Human rights activists say the government&#39;s response has been brutal.
Eyewitnesses claimed that police officers shot and killed dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
Video footage of the protests, believed to have been taken late last or early this year, shows young people being beaten with sticks by security officers as they were put up against a wall with their hands.
The United Nations&#39; top human rights official is now calling for a thorough investigation.
&quot;It has always been difficult to keep this country from collapsing, and it will continue to be even more difficult,&quot; said Rashid Abdi, head of the Horn of Africa Project at the International Crisis Research Group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is supported by the West.
The US military and intelligence services are working closely with the Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
The Ethiopian economy is developing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly - there is even a new commuter train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And its streets are generally quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly a model of democracy - human rights organizations constantly mention government repression - the opposition on the territory of the state was suppressed, due to the fact that dissidents were effectively silenced.
Many of them were exiled, imprisoned, killed or banished to remote deserts.
But this may change.
&quot;If people are constantly suppressed and left with no other option but to protest, an uprising will break out,&quot; said Seyum Teshome, a lecturer at a university in central Ethiopia.
All the youth are protesting.
The generation is protesting.
Complaints are numerous, ranging from land use to the seizure of power by the government coalition.
After last year&#39;s widely criticized elections, the government party and its allies completely ousted the opposition and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions are rising along the Eritrean border; the fight over this vague, disputed border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less wiped out in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit the unrest and rearm.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings, boiling in the depths of the soul for several years, flare up now.
The first, it would seem, is completely harmless: smartphones.
In the last couple of years alone, large numbers of Ethiopians have been able to connect on social media as cheap smartphones have become commonplace and internet service has improved.
Even when the government closes access to Facebook and Twitter, as often happens, especially during protests, many people still find it possible to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that was how they organized for the protests.
The second is that there is more solidarity between the Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
For centuries, the Amhara of the predominantly Christian highlands of Ethiopia have prospered in politics and business by exploiting the Oromo, many of whom are Muslim and live in the lowlands.
But this is also changing.
&quot;We will act together under a single command,&quot; said Mulatu Gemechu, the leader of the Oromo.
The largest protests took place in the Amhara and Oromo regions.
Many in Amhara and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is being unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which makes up about 6 percent of the population and controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third reason for unrest is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia&#39;s acting prime minister for 17 years, until his death from an unknown illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts say he was especially adept at spotting early signs of discontent and using scouts to gather intelligence and neutralize opponents.
&quot;The current regime lacks common sense,&quot; said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia&#39;s new prime minister, Hailemariam Desaleni, came out of nowhere and took Meles&#39; place.
Unlike Meles, who hailed from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is a southerner.
Analysts say he is not trusted by the Tigray-controlled security forces.
Many fear that this will lead to more bloodshed as a result.
Ethiopia last experienced such unrest in 2005, after thousands of people protested what analysts said appeared to be an election that the government botched and then rigged.
In the repression that followed, many Protestants were killed, although in fewer numbers than in recent months, and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts commended Ethiopia&#39;s leaders for visionary infrastructure developments such as a new intercity train and significant progress in the fight against poverty.
But it is clear that this did not stop the growth of internal dissatisfaction with the Ethiopian government.
And it takes a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, a city in Amhara, attacked businesses owned by Tigray, and anti-Tygray hatred on social media is becoming all-encompassing.
Analysts say the protesters are putting the United States and other Western allies in an uncomfortable position.
The US government has used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced that it has closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand, it does not want its ally to lose power in an already unstable region.
&quot;And this tightrope will be difficult to walk on,&quot; Abdi said.
