The Depressive Food of Depression at The Tight Meal
In March 1933, shortly after ascending to the presidency, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat down to dinner in the Oval Office.
As a gourmet, President Roosevelt loved Fifth Avenue trendy dishes such as foie gras and Maryland turtle soup.
His menu that day was more modest: stuffed eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes and, for dessert, prune pudding.
“It was an act of culinary solidarity with the people who were suffering,” said Jane Siegelman.
Her husband Andrew Coe added: &quot;It was also a message to Americans about how to eat.&quot;
The couple, who live in Brooklyn Heights, are experts in food history.
Kowa&#39;s latest book, Chinese Stew, focused on Chinese food in America, and Siegelman told the story of life in a rented apartment on the Lower East Side through food in her book 97 Orchard Street.
Their newest collaboration, The Hearty Meal, to be published Tuesday by Harper, is the story of American food in the Great Depression.
In a show of culinary solidarity of their own, they met the reporter for dinner at Eisenberg&#39;s Sandwich Shop, a tiny, unpretentious eatery in the Flatiron Quarter that has been in business since the 1929 Stock Market Crash.
Siegelman, 54, ordered cream cheese and a sandwich with olive slices, while Coe, 57, ordered turkey, mashed potatoes and vegetable mix.
When the reporter ordered the meatloaf, the couple saw it as a fitting starting point for a discussion about Depression-era food.
&quot;The rolls were in high demand,&quot; Siegelman said.
There was peanut roll, liver roll, bean roll.
They were made from the main ingredient and cheap products that allowed the ingredient to stretch.
Imagine that you have eaten as many peanuts as you need for dinner.
Kou winced.
&quot;Probably, he was lying in the stomach with a stone,&quot; he said.
In the years before the Depression, the American table, especially in rural areas, was a smorgasbord.
Groups of women cooked for the male farm workers, and a freshly baked pie was served for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
It was the Americans who sent food to starving Europeans during World War I. &quot;The Heavy Meal&quot; describes how the country coped with the fact that it suddenly ceased to be a country of abundance.
&quot;It was a time when food became a central, difficult topic for Americans,&quot; Coe said, explaining why he and his wife decided to write about it.
Just as challenging was the new budget ration: arcane dishes such as rolls and casseroles became staples; A casserole is &quot;a great way to use leftovers,&quot; Siegelman said, &quot;because chefs could hide unappetizing ingredients under a thick layer of sauce.
Fresh fruits have been replaced by cheaper dried fruits.
Meat, for many years the staple of American food, has become a sparingly distributed luxury.
People tried strange concoctions because energy and nutritional value became more important than taste and even culinary common sense.
While doing research for a book that includes recipes, Siegelman prepared a dish from that era: baked onions stuffed with peanut butter.
&quot;This addition to the dining table was not a success,&quot; Coe said.
Siegelman added: &quot;It was very strange.&quot;
Peanut butter doesn&#39;t go well with baked onions.
This was typical for many household recipes.
Like never before, and never since, home economics experts—including Louise Stanley, chief of the federal Bureau of Home Economics from 1923 to 1943—managed the nation&#39;s eating habits.
By publishing recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines, they encouraged women to become &quot;budgeters,&quot; rise to the challenge of transforming squash like pureed spaghetti with carrots into delicious meals.
The &quot;Heavy Meal&quot; is a feast of curious historical facts.
Particularly poignant are stories about the government&#39;s response to starving citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover&#39;s &quot;let them eat pies&quot; stance.
While publicly extolling the simple Iowa farm food of his childhood, he ate like the sophisticated millionaire he had become.
&quot;He liked continental cuisine, like fish with cucumber sauce,&quot; Coe said.
He ate in a practically gilded dining room, wearing a tuxedo.
He was fantastically out of touch with reality.
President Roosevelt might have made the same mistake if his wife, Eleanor, had not advised him to set an example with his own stomach.
According to the book, Eleanor Roosevelt hired a housekeeper with no interest in taste, which led the White House to &quot;eat not only the dullest food in Washington, but sometimes the most disgustingly cooked.&quot;
Many of the culinary techniques of the Depression era were forgotten once the country got back on its feet.
Their legacy is our ongoing focus on calories and nutrition, Siegelman says, and how science has been used in food preparation.
The couple say that while writing the book, they got a better understanding of Siegelman&#39;s mother&#39;s eating habits - that she couldn&#39;t throw away food, for example.
&quot;She had a serious fear of casual eating,&quot; Coe said.
Siegelman recalls, &quot;She literally poisoned people.&quot;
There was one unpleasant incident with profiteroles.
When the plates at Eisenberg&#39;s were empty, she and Coe pulled out a dessert they&#39;d made at home: the prune dessert that President Roosevelt had for lunch.
&quot;It&#39;s called prune mousse,&quot; Siegelman said, adding that it was a common practice to give humble recipes catchy names.
There was no whipped cream, just prunes, some flour, sugar, water, and cinnamon.
Everyone reluctantly plunged the spoon into the viscous, brown, sticky substance.
Surprisingly, it was good.
Coe asked for more twice.
In a confident budgeter&#39;s voice, he told his wife, &quot;A few chopped walnuts would do the trick.&quot;
