NASA Climate Model: Venus Was Once Habitable
Venus may have once been habitable, according to NASA&#39;s new climate model estimates.
Scientists at NASA&#39;s Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model for exploring Venus&#39; past using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was developed to determine whether Venus, with its hot, waterless surface and atmosphere saturated with carbon dioxide, could ever have experienced Earth-like conditions.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus&#39;s slow rotation is due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulations suggest that Venus could probably have a thin atmosphere like Earth&#39;s and still rotate slowly.
The model also considered the topography of early Venus.
The planet, in all likelihood, had more dry regions than Earth, but it once had enough water and enough geographic variability to support life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from a sun that was 30 percent dimmer.
&quot;According to the GISS model, Venus&#39;s slow rotation exposes its dayside to the sun for nearly two months at a time,&quot; GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio explained in a press release.
This warms the planet&#39;s surface and produces rain, which creates a thick cloud layer that acts as an umbrella, shielding the planet&#39;s surface from much of the sun&#39;s heat.
The result is average climatic temperatures that are, surprisingly, several degrees colder than today on Earth.
The model shows a history of Venus that is similar to the evolution previously assumed by planetary scientists.
Even though Venus may have once been habitable, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapor was scorched by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen evaporated, only a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect remained - that is, Venus as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new climate model for Venus in Geophysical Research Letters.
