Kepler measures the speed of rotation of stars in the Pleiades cluster
The latest Kepler space telescope mission has helped astronomers assemble the most comprehensive catalog of the rotational speeds of stars in the Pleiades cluster.
The new data is helping astronomers understand why the stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, as well as how rotation periods correlate with planet formation.
&quot;We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age, and even the history of its solar system,&quot; Louise Ryball, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the California State University, said in a press release. technological institute.
The Pleiades cluster is located 445 light years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster are now just reaching maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They are spinning as fast as they&#39;ll never be again.
At their peak rotational speeds, these maturing stars throw out large amounts of stellar wind.
As they travel through the magnetic fields of stars, these winds exert a decelerating effect on the stars.
As a star ages, its rotation speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures each star&#39;s rotation rate by tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable star spots, such as sunspots.
The latest catalog of rotation rates suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Ryball compares the stars to dancers: the larger ones pirouette slower than the smaller ones.
&quot;In the Pleiadian ballet, we see that those that rotate slowly are usually more massive, while those that rotate faster are usually very light stars,&quot; Ryball said.
Because the Pleiades Cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars with rotational speeds.
&quot;The Pleiades star cluster provides a starting point for theoretical models of the rotation of stars, both younger and older,&quot; Ryball said.
We still want to know a lot about how, where and why stars slow down their rotation and hang their &quot;dancing shoes&quot; on a nail, figuratively speaking.
Ryball and her colleagues have detailed their latest analysis of the Pleiadian rotation rates in three new papers, soon to be published in The Astronomical Journal.
