Compared to the 1993 figure, the Gini coefficient, which is a standard measure of inequality in income distribution, has fallen by 15 points.
Then, 23 years ago, this figure was one of the highest in the world.
And the poverty rate has fallen from 69% in 1993 to less than 30%.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (less than $1.90 a day) has also fallen, from almost 53% to less than 23%.
Namibia also has the highest free speech rating in Africa, according to Reporters Without Borders.
The country has significantly outpaced the United States and other wealthy states.
