Of course, Namibia also has some problems.
The unemployment rate, at least according to traditional methods of estimation, is still quite high - almost 28%.
And, like other countries in the region, Namibia has a high rate of HIV/AIDS with nearly 17% of the population being infected.
The World Bank estimates that Namibia is an upper-middle-income country, but the authorities insist that their country is in fact a developing country.
Namibia certainly faces some of the challenges that are inherent in underdeveloped economies.
The state has to develop a very large and arid country with a small population.
Isolated nomadic tribes of hunter-gatherers live in the deserts of the country, which one way or another must be integrated into modern society, without losing their identity.
Integrating people who a quarter of a century ago were on the periphery of the world economy is not an easy task for any country.
For Namibia, it is even more difficult: like any other country in the world, it is facing the effects of climate change.
However, Namibia did not even think to give up, the country is solving the problems it faces.
Almost immediately after independence, the authorities set about building a diversified economy and a cohesive society.
Notably, rival political factions have come together to work for the common good.
Indeed, Namibia provides cheap medical care not only to its own citizens, but also to its neighbors.
About 15-20% of visitors to health facilities in northern Namibia are Angolan citizens.
No one in Namibia talks about building a wall to separate the country from its poor and corrupt neighbors.
The Namibians realized that they did not choose their neighbors, and therefore decided not to conflict with them, but to cooperate - to share scarce water resources, take part in regional medical projects, encourage investment and student exchange.
Moreover, the Namibian government rightly judged that rich natural resources could easily become a curse, making the few rich at the expense of the many.
The authorities understand that the income from Namibia&#39;s natural wealth must be invested in infrastructure and productive capacity.
They also recognize that it would be irresponsible not to seek maximum profit from the sale of the country&#39;s resources, and are reviewing investment laws and mining contracts to ensure that this is the case.
Transparency is critical to this process, which is why strong government support for free speech is so important.
As head of state Hage Geingob noted, the media often say what he does not like.
But after fighting for freedom from apartheid in South Africa, Namibia must defend the freedoms it has gained, the president says.
Not all of Namibia&#39;s key resources are exhaustible.
Some - such as fishing - are renewable, and the government is working hard to preserve and strengthen them.
Every year, over a million foreign tourists visit the country.
Namibia shows that even those countries that start out with serious flaws - racism, colonialism, inequality and underdevelopment - can get on the path to shared prosperity.
Her achievement deserves international recognition and emulation.
Many have heard about the &quot;Gold of Varna&quot; - the oldest golden objects created by man (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps this was the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavations of the Varna necropolis, a fantastic number of gold artifacts were found - more than three thousand with a total weight of 6 kilograms.
Only from one burial, known as &quot;grave No. 43&quot;, 990 gold objects with a total weight of more than 1.5 kg were recovered.
However, the official status of the oldest gold in the world may soon pass to a plain-looking bead found by archaeologists in July this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement known as Tell Yunatsite.
Unlike Varna, a port city, Tell Yunatsite is located far from the sea, near the village of Yunatsite in the Pazardzhik region.
The bead is a gold strip rolled into a ring.
Yavor Boyadzhiev, head of the excavations at Tell Yunatsite, dated the find to 4600 BC and said it was at least 200 years older than the Varna gold.
Treasures of Varna, we recall, date back to approximately the same period, 4600 - 4200 years. BC.
There are currently no technologies that allow metal dating with impeccable accuracy.
Where is the confidence in which gold is more ancient?
Evidently Prof. Boyadjiev knows more than he told Reuters: &quot;I&#39;m quite sure that Yunatsite&#39;s gold is older than Varna&#39;s.&quot;
This is a find of extreme importance: it looks like a tiny object, but it is large enough to take its rightful place in history.
In an interview with Reuters, Boyadzhiev said that in the near future, scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as re-examine and more thoroughly the archaeological layer where the gold artifact was found.
This will help date the bead as accurately as possible.
The location of the find also explains a lot.
Tell Yunatsite is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
Tell Yunatsite is currently considered the oldest &quot;city&quot; in Europe.
Tell was founded by the descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
Over the following centuries, metalworking flourished in this region, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In Russian historiography, this archaeological community has a special name: the Balkan-Carpathian metallurgical province.
In the 5th millennium BC, urban-type settlements began to appear around metalworking centers.
Now they are called the oldest cities in Europe.
Of these, Tell Yunatsite is perhaps the most ancient, since artifacts from 4900 BC were found here.
I would call Tell Yunazi the prototype of a modern city, although this is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
&quot;This place is a thousand years older than Sumer,&quot; says Boyadzhiev, referring to the conventional wisdom that urban culture originated in southern Mesopotamia - modern-day Iraq.
The first cities in the usual sense of the word arose there.
The excavations of Tell Yunatsite have been carried out since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists have unearthed almost 12 hectares, which is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of the fortress wall were found, which once reached three meters in height.
Little has been preserved of the houses and workshops, but archaeologists clearly distinguish between streets, public buildings, urban dense buildings, the &quot;business center&quot; and residential outskirts.
Tell Yunatsite is often called the &quot;Bird City&quot;: dozens of clay figurines of birds have been found here.
All birds are depicted in a state of rest, hence the assumption that they were not decorative objects, but the object of a local cult.
The &quot;Bird City&quot; was destroyed around 4100 BC - possibly by Indo-European tribes who came from the northeast.
The nomads had no cities, but they had horses and weapons.
Three-meter fortress walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists have found obvious signs of a brutal massacre: the remains of old people, women and children were found inside the houses with traces of wounds inflicted by battle axes.
New finds and new facts appear every year, changing the usual ideas about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the &quot;lost&quot; first civilization of Europe, which originated in the Balkans.
A powerful incentive in the search for this civilization was the &quot;gold of Varna&quot;, found relatively recently, in 1972.
It is logical that the golden luxury of Varna should have been preceded by something - something like a tiny golden bead created in Tell Yunatsite.
