Facebook and ad blockers unleashed an &quot;arms race&quot;
Facebook&#39;s recent introduction of technology to prevent ad-hiding on social media pages has provoked retaliatory action by developers of ad-blocking solutions.
AdBlock Plus has released an &quot;antidote&quot;, but Facebook plans to make it useless soon.
This is how AdBlock Plus advertised their new technology, which is likely to remain effective for a short time.
The social network representatives noted that, in an effort to deceive the new technology of &quot;unblockable&quot; advertising, the solution from AdBlock Plus, along with commercial ads, also blocks many ordinary posts from friends or pages.
Facebook expressed regret with this policy of AdBlock Plus and promised to solve the problem soon.
As a source among the developers of the social network told TechCrunch, the code that makes AdBlock Plus useless on the Facebook desktop site will be ready within the next few hours.
Thus, the social network and blockers unleashed a kind of “arms race”, trying to beat each other, while users who missed interesting posts from friends or saw ads where they were not used to seeing them became the affected side.
The ethical aspects of ad blocking have been hotly debated lately.
